summary:
We are building a Socratic tutor agent that guides students through problems by asking targeted questions instead of handing out answers. It gives teachers a scalable way to provide personalized feedback and helps students practice independent reasoning. I will walk through the code I actually wrote to ship this. What you'll need Python 3.10 or newer The OpenAI SDK: pip install openai An Oxlo.ai API key from https://portal.oxlo.ai Step 1: Set up the Oxlo.ai client I instantiate the OpenAI-compatible client pointing at Oxlo.ai and make a quick health-check call to confirm the key works. If you want to experiment at zero cost, deepseek-v3.2 is available on Oxlo.ai's free tier and uses the same client. from openai import OpenAI client = OpenAI(base_url="https://api.oxlo.ai/v1", api_key="YOUR_OXLO_API_KEY") response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=[ {"role": "user", "content": "Say hello"}, ], ) print(response.choices[0].message.content) Step 2: Lock in the Socratic system prompt The system prompt is the only guardrail that keeps the model from just solving the problem for the student. I keep it in a constant so I can iterate without touching business logic. SYSTEM_PROMPT = """You are a patient Socratic tutor for high school math and science. Rules: 1. Never give the final answer directly. 2. Ask one or two guiding questions that help the student discover the next step. 3. If the student is stuck, break the problem into smaller parts. 4. Keep responses concise, under 120 words. 5. Encourage the student when they make progress.""" Step 3: Build the single-turn tutor function This function takes a student message and returns the tutor's response. I use llama-3.3-70b because it follows instructions reliably for dialogue tasks. from openai import OpenAI client = OpenAI(base_url="https://api.oxlo.ai/v1", api_key="YOUR_OXLO_API_KEY") SYSTEM_PROMPT = """You are a patient Socratic tutor for high school math and science. Rules: 1. Never give the final answer directly. 2. Ask one or two guiding questions that help the student discover the next step. 3. If the student is stuck, break the problem into smaller parts. 4. Keep responses concise, under 120 words. 5. Encourage the student when they make progress.""" def tutor_reply(student_message: str) -> str: response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=[ {"role": "system", "content": SYSTEM_PROMPT}, {"role": "user", "content": student_message}, ], ) return response.choices[0].message.content if __name__ == "__main__": print(tutor_reply("How do I solve for x in 3x + 5 = 20?")) Step 4: Add multi-turn memory Real tutoring requires context. I replace the single-turn function with a small class that appends messages to a list and sends the full history on every call. Oxlo.ai's request-based pricing means I do not have to worry about the token count growing during a long study session. from openai import OpenAI client = OpenAI(base_url="https://api.oxlo.ai/v1", api_key="YOUR_OXLO_API_KEY") SYSTEM_PROMPT = """You are a patient Socratic tutor for high school math and science. Rules: 1. Never give the final answer directly. 2. Ask one or two guiding questions that help the student discover the next step. 3. If the student is stuck, break the problem into smaller parts. 4. Keep responses concise, under 120 words. 5. Encourage the student when they make progress.""" class SocraticTutor: def __init__(self): self.history = [{"role": "system", "content": SYSTEM_PROMPT}] def chat(self, student_message: str) -> str: self.history.append({"role": "user", "content": student_message}) response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=self.history, ) reply = response.choices[0].message.content self.history.append({"role": "assistant", "content": reply}) return reply if __name__ == "__main__": tutor = SocraticTutor() print(tutor.chat("How do I solve for x in 3x + 5 = 20?")) print(tutor.chat("I subtracted 5 from both sides. Now what?")) Step 5: Generate a practice problem and evaluate answers I add two utility methods. One generates a fresh problem with qwen-3-32b, and another grades the student's attempt with llama-3.3-70b. from openai import OpenAI client = OpenAI(base_url="https://api.oxlo.ai/v1", api_key="YOUR_OXLO_API_KEY") SYSTEM_PROMPT = """You are a patient Socratic tutor for high school math and science. Rules: 1. Never give the final answer directly. 2. Ask one or two guiding questions that help the student discover the next step. 3. If the student is stuck, break the problem into smaller parts. 4. Keep responses concise, under 120 words. 5. Encourage the student when they make progress.""" class SocraticTutor: def __init__(self): self.history = [{"role": "system", "content": SYSTEM_PROMPT}] def chat(self, student_message: str) -> str: self.history.append({"role": "user", "content": student_message}) response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=self.history, ) reply = response.choices[0].message.content self.history.append({"role": "assistant", "content": reply}) return reply def quiz(self, topic: str) -> str: response = client.chat.completions.create( model="qwen-3-32b", messages=[ {"role": "system", "content": "Generate one high school level math problem. Output only the problem statement, no solution."}, {"role": "user", "content": f"Topic: {topic}"}, ], ) return response.choices[0].message.content.strip() def grade(self, problem: str, answer: str) -> str: response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=[ {"role": "system", "content": "Grade the answer. If wrong, give a Socratic hint, not the solution."}, {"role": "user", "content": f"Problem: {problem}
Answer: {answer}"}, ], ) return response.choices[0].message.content.strip() Run it Here is the complete script and the output from a live session. from openai import OpenAI client = OpenAI(base_url="https://api.oxlo.ai/v1", api_key="YOUR_OXLO_API_KEY") SYSTEM_PROMPT = """You are a patient Socratic tutor for high school math and science. Rules: 1. Never give the final answer directly. 2. Ask one or two guiding questions that help the student discover the next step. 3. If the student is stuck, break the problem into smaller parts. 4. Keep responses concise, under 120 words. 5. Encourage the student when they make progress.""" class SocraticTutor: def __init__(self): self.history = [{"role": "system", "content": SYSTEM_PROMPT}] def chat(self, student_message: str) -> str: self.history.append({"role": "user", "content": student_message}) response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=self.history, ) reply = response.choices[0].message.content self.history.append({"role": "assistant", "content": reply}) return reply def quiz(self, topic: str) -> str: response = client.chat.completions.create( model="qwen-3-32b", messages=[ {"role": "system", "content": "Generate one high school level math problem. Output only the problem statement, no solution."}, {"role": "user", "content": f"Topic: {topic}"}, ], ) return response.choices[0].message.content.strip() def grade(self, problem: str, answer: str) -> str: response = client.chat.completions.create( model="llama-3.3-70b", messages=[ {"role": "system", "content": "Grade the answer. If wrong, give a Socratic hint, not the solution."}, {"role": "user", "content": f"Problem: {problem}
Answer: {answer}"}, ], ) return response.choices[0].message.content.strip() if __name__ == "__main__": tutor = SocraticTutor() print("=== Tutor Session ===") print(tutor.chat("I need help with 3x + 7 = 22")) print(tutor.chat("I subtracted 7 and got 3x = 15")) print(tutor.chat("Then I divided by 3 and got x = 5")) print("
=== Quiz ===") problem = tutor.quiz("systems of equations") print(problem) print("
=== Grade ===") print(tutor.grade(problem, "x = 2, y = 4")) Example output: === Tutor Session === What operation undoes adding 7 to both sides? Great. Now what do you divide by to isolate x? Exactly. x = 5. Well done. === Quiz === Solve the system: 2x + 3y = 12 x - y = 1 === Grade === Check your substitution. Does x = 2 and y = 4 satisfy the second equation? Next steps Wrap this class in a FastAPI endpoint so students can interact with it from a browser or mobile app. If you want to grade handwritten work, swap the chat model for kimi-k2.6 and pipe image inputs through Oxlo.ai's vision-compatible endpoints. For workloads like this, where a tutoring session can easily grow to dozens of turns with long context, Oxlo.ai's per-request pricing keeps costs predictable regardless of how long the conversation grows. See https://oxlo.ai/pricing to find a plan that fits your volume.
